<div class="cs-section">
  <div class="cs-content">
    <h2>ActiveSync has limitations</h2>
    <p>Microsoft Exchange offers a lovely feature called Public Folders, which allows companies to create a single pool of contacts, calendar events, etc. and share them amongst employees. Outlook natively supports these features, and it integrates nicely. Even better, access to these shares is managed via Active Directory, so IT has full control.</p>
    <p>A client approached the IT team at Immense Networks wanting to access this data on their mobile devices. While a user&rsquo;s contacts, emails, and calendars sync flawlessly with nearly any device, Public Folder synchronization is a lacking feature of ActiveSync.</p>
    <p>So, we looked for solutions.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="cs-section bg-[#f2ffe3]">
  <div class="cs-content">
    <h2>Building a SaaS</h2>
    <p>Other companies have developed solutions to this problem; most require users to download a 3rd party app on their device, then it forces them to use that app rather than the device&rsquo;s native Contacts and Calendar apps. This was cumbersome and unacceptable.</p>
    <blockquote>We wanted to integrate Public Folders natively into a device’s core experience.</blockquote>
    <p>We only found a single product on the market which worked natively on a user&rsquo;s device, called numbered. This initially seemed great, but further inspection revealed 2 terrible things:</p>
    <div class="text-base grid md:grid-cols-2 md:gap-16">
      <div>
        <h3>A program must be installed onto the Exchange server.</h3>
        <p>This is terrible for so many reasons. What if a company is using Office 365? What if they don&rsquo;t have their own Exchange server? What if an IT company has a server with 200 separate  company Exchange accounts on it?</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3>Information is replicated into each user&rsquo;s Personal Mailbox.</h3>
        <p>So, Outlook hits Public Folders natively, other devices hit a subfolder with duplicates of Public Folder data, and we&rsquo;re supposed to trust that numbered will sync it all with no issues. This seemed overengineered.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>Our search continued for an acceptable solution to recommend to our clients, but the inevitable conclusion was clear: <strong>the only way to give our clients the experience they deserved was to build it ourselves</strong>.</p>
    <img class="md:mx-auto" src="/static/images/projects/pfsync/feature-how-it-works.png" alt="How pfsync works">
    <p>The idea was simple. We would build a dedicated web service to extend ActiveSync&rsquo;s functionality to include Public Folder data. We would then authenticate against Exchange servers as individual users, which would limit access to Public Folders based on that user&rsquo;s permissions. We then wrap everything in a subscription-based SaaS and start promoting it.</p>
    <p>Immense was in a unique position to test the service with select IT clients, eventually get them on a monthly retainer for it, then ultimately offer it to the masses.</p>
  </div>
</div>


<div class="cs-section">
