    <h2>Making pfsync marketable</h2>
    <p>While backend developers were building a functional prototype, I pursued selling a magnificent product. The name pfsync came so naturally, and the remaining discovery snowballed from there.</p>
    <p>pfsync would be an extension of the ActiveSync protocol, filling in the gaps to offer the user a truly native experience regardless of device. This bond with ActiveSync served as inspiration for pfsync’s identity, right down to the green color scheme.</p>
    <img class="mx-auto" src="/static/images/projects/pfsync/pfsync-brand-breakdown.jpg" alt="pfsync logo">
    <p>I created something reminiscent of the ActiveSync logo from the Windows XP era, which I felt would resonate with this product’s primary userbase – passionate IT professionals who have likely been in this game for while.</p>
  </div>
</div>

